"{\"uid\": \"express.co.uk-sport-othersport-1897765-Team-GB-Noah-Williams-Olympic-Games\", \"text\": \"  Noah Williams wants to honour the memory of the coach who ignited his Olympic dreams by securing a medal in Paris.  The diver from Hackney finished 27th on his Olympic debut in Tokyo, missing out on a semi-final attempt, and later sent a message to his followers onInstagramwhich read: \\\"Thank you for all the support, I am sorry I could not do you proud x\\\".  But performances in the pool were soon placed firmly into perspective after the death of his much-loved coach Dave Jenkins in October 2021.  The 23-year-old's life was turned upside down and he considered retiring from the sport he loved.  \\\"A lot of this (Olympic) cycle is done in his memory,\\\" Williams said. \\\"I wanted to quit after he passed.  \\\"It's hard when someone passes who is your main motivator, he was training me for events.  \\\"I really did not enjoy diving after that. It still would have been completely different if he just quit, diving would be different, but because he did pass away, it was a lot to process.  \\\"It was the first time in my life that I'd had anything like that to deal with.\\\"  Jenkins was a mentor and a friend to Williams, who had been his coach's prot\\u00e9g\\u00e9 since the age of 16 at London Aquatics Centre.  But after taking time to process the grief, a switch flicked and he was all of a sudden embarking on a second Olympic quest.  \\\"I stuck through it and I ended up thinking the opposite, that I could not quit because I wanted to do something in his memory,\\\" he said.  \\\"I did not know what else to do apart from dive.  \\\"I could not leave it on Tokyo so hopefully I can do well in Paris for him.\\\"  Williams is one of over 1,000 elite athletes on UK Sport's National Lottery-funded World Class Programme, allowing them to train full time, have access to the world's best coaches and benefit from pioneering medical support - this is vital for their pathway to the Paris 2024 Games.  He has been selected alongside Team GB mainstay Tom Daley, approaching his fifth Games, in the men's 10m synchro event for Paris 2024.  They secured a quota spot with World Championships silver in Doha earlier this year, their first international competition as a pair, and Daley will now go for a golden title defence in France having triumphed alongside Matty Lee in Tokyo.  \\\"I do not think people realise how good Tom is,\\\" Williams said. \\\"There is no one else in the world who could have two years out, come back and be a world medallist and world champion in the team event.  \\\"He's insanely hard-working and talented, he's miles above everyone else.  \\\"Anything can happen on the day and we have done really well this year so I hope I can help him out.  \\\"Individually it's quite lonely, synchro is the closest we can get to a team sport and it's a lot more enjoyable, sharing the whole event with someone,\\\" he said.  \\\"You get to share the pressure, it does not feel as daunting, especially when it's Tom. I get to just be there so I like it so far.  \\\"Tom is a massive name and the pressure is on him - that's good for me and how I compete.  \\\"At that first Olympics, I had to wait until the last day to compete so it was literally just me and Tom.  We use your sign-up to provide content in ways you have consented to and to improve our understanding of you. This may include adverts from us and 3rd parties based on our understanding. You can unsubscribe at any time. Read ourPrivacy Policy  \\\"I knew he was going to do really well and I put a lot of expectation on myself and it did not work. I have learned a lot from it and I have come back stronger.\\\"  National Lottery players raise more than \\u00a330million a week for good causes including vital funding into sport - from grassroots to elite. Find out how your numbers make amazing happen at: www.lotterygoodcauses.org.uk #TNLAthletes #MakeAmazingHappen  SEARCH  CONNECT WITH US  TODAY'S PAPER  See today's front and back pages, download the newspaper, order back issues and use the historic Daily Express newspaper archive.  EXPRESS.CO.UK  Daily Express uses notifications to keep you updated\"}"